-- Nordic Stocks: Christian Hansen, Electrolux, Ericsson, Yara Are Active
-- Adam Ewing
-- 2010-07-19T13:02:43Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-19/nordic-stocks-christian-hansen-electrolux-ericsson-yara-are-active.html

          
          
             The  Stoxx Nordic 30 Index , the
benchmark measure for the region, rose 0.4 percent to 6,529.41
at 3 p.m., in Stockholm, rebounding from the 2.1 percent loss on
July 16.  
 The  OMX Stockholm 30 Index  rose 0.8 percent and  Norway’s
OBX Index  climbed 0.8 percent. The  Helsinki Index  gained 0.5
percent and the  Copenhagen 20 Index  fell 0.4 percent.  
 The following companies’ shares were among the most active
in Nordic markets today. Symbols are in parentheses.  
 Boliden AB  (BOL SS) slumped 3.1 percent to 83.85 kronor,
the biggest drop since July 1. The Swedish copper and zinc miner
fell after its second-quarter earnings lagged analyst estimates.  
 Christian Hansen Holding A/S  (CHR DC) rose 2 percent to 101
kroner, erasing its 1 percent drop on July 16. The Danish maker
of food ingredients was rated “overweight” at JPMorgan Chase &
Co. in new coverage.  
 Electrolux AB  (ELUXB SS) fell the most this month, tumbling
6.2 percent to 156.6 kronor. The world’s second-largest
appliance maker said that southern European demand weakened
“substantially” at the end of the second quarter.  
 Ericsson AB  (ERICB SS), the world’s biggest maker of
mobile-phone networks, rose 2.4 percent to 86.3 kronor, paring
its 2.3 percent loss on July 16. The company said it won a
three-year order from China Mobile Ltd. “to improve its network
quality and operational efficiency.”  
 Metro International SA  (MTROSDBB SS) tumbled 8.5 percent to
1.18 kronor. The Swedish publisher of free newspapers reported a
second-quarter net loss of 389,000 euros ($504,000).  
 Nokia Oyj  (NOK1V FH) rose 1.3 percent to 6.86 euros, its
fourth gain in five days. The world’s biggest phone maker’s
network joint venture, Nokia Siemens Networks, agreed to buy
Motorola Inc.’s wireless-network equipment business for $1.2
billion.  
 Norwegian Energy Co.  (NOR NO) rose 1.6 percent to 12.55
euros, paring its 3.9 percent slide on July 16. The North Sea
oil and natural-gas explorer has sold its 20 percent interest in
the PL378 license to Talisman Energy Norge AS for $43 million.
The Norwegian authorities still need to approve the deal.  
